# quincy-client / quincy-server — Quincy: post-quantum QUIC-based VPN.
#                  Server + client binaries that establish a tunneled
#                  TUN interface between client and server over IETF
#                  QUIC (RFC 9000-9002) with TLS 1.3 + post-quantum
#                  key-exchange via aws-lc-rs's hybrid Kyber768-
#                  X25519, so the tunnel survives the eventual
#                  arrival of cryptographically-relevant quantum
#                  computers without re-handshake migration (Rust,
#                  307★)
#
# upstream: https://github.com/quincy-rs/quincy
#           (server binary at quincy-server/, client binary at
#           quincy-client/ in the workspace)
# author : Jakub Kubík (jakub.kubik.it@protonmail.com) — also the
#          author of the broader quincy-rs organization tooling
# license: AGPL-3.0-or-later
#
# Source-direct completion: every flag below is verbatim from
# quincy-server/src/main.rs + quincy-client/src/bin/main.rs on the
# quincy-rs/quincy tip — clap `#[derive(Parser)]` Args structs parsed
# exactly as declared.  The CLI surface is intentionally minimal
# (only --config-path + --env-prefix on both binaries) because
# Quincy is configuration-file-driven — the operationally meaningful
# config lives in server.toml / client.toml (specifying QUIC
# endpoint addresses, TUN interface name, TLS cert paths, the
# routing-table push-rules, authentication mode, etc) and the
# `--env-prefix QUINCY_` env-var binding lets all of those settings
# also be supplied via environment variables (e.g.
# `QUINCY_QUIC__ENDPOINT=0.0.0.0:55555` overrides the
# `[quic].endpoint` key in the TOML).
#
# Direct deps from Cargo.toml (selected):
#   quinn                "^0.11.8" ← canonical Rust IETF QUIC
#                                     implementation library (this
#                                     axis) — by Quinn org (Dirkjan
#                                     Ochtman + Benjamin Saunders +
#                                     Ralith); pure-Rust async-first
#                                     implementation of RFC 9000-9002
#                                     (QUIC v1) + RFC 9114 (HTTP/3
#                                     header compression via hyperium/
#                                     h3 sibling) + RFC 9221
#                                     (unreliable datagrams) + the
#                                     ECN / congestion-control /
#                                     loss-recovery / stream
#                                     multiplexing surface QUIC
#                                     demands.  Pluggable crypto
#                                     backend: rustls (default) for
#                                     pure-Rust TLS 1.3, or
#                                     `rustls-aws-lc-rs` for AWS's
#                                     FIPS-validated libcrypto-compat
#                                     backend (which is what Quincy
#                                     uses — aws-lc-rs is also where
#                                     the Kyber768-X25519 post-
#                                     quantum hybrid key-exchange
#                                     primitive lives, hence Quincy's
#                                     "post-quantum" framing).  Tokio
#                                     runtime integration via the
#                                     `runtime-tokio` feature
#                                     (alternative is `runtime-
#                                     async-std`).  Platform-verifier
#                                     for native cert-store
#                                     validation on Mac/Windows/
#                                     Linux.  THE Rust answer to
#                                     "speak QUIC from a Rust
#                                     process" — used by Cloudflare's
#                                     quiche-wireguard-prototype,
#                                     iroh (the p2p QUIC mesh
#                                     library), cloudflare/pingora
#                                     (Pingora's QUIC stack),
#                                     hyperium/h3 (the HTTP/3
#                                     library), tokio-rs/tokio-quic-
#                                     interop test runner, salvo
#                                     (Rust web framework's HTTP/3
#                                     support), shadowsocks/qtun
#                                     (QUIC obfuscation plugin),
#                                     blockworks-foundation/lite-rpc
#                                     (Solana RPC over QUIC),
#                                     bytedance/g3 (enterprise proxy
#                                     stack), and Quincy itself.
#                                     Quincy uses Quinn inside the
#                                     QuincyServer::accept_loop and
#                                     QuincyClient::connect_loop —
#                                     all encrypted tunnel packets
#                                     between client and server flow
#                                     through Quinn's
#                                     `Connection::open_bi` /
#                                     `accept_bi` bidirectional
#                                     streams (one stream per
#                                     direction of the tunneled TUN
#                                     interface's L3 packets).
#   rustls + rustls-pemfile +        (TLS 1.3 with the aws-lc-rs
#       aws-lc-rs                     backend selected — provides
#                                     the post-quantum
#                                     Kyber768-X25519 hybrid
#                                     key-exchange that the
#                                     marketing-name "post-
#                                     quantum QUIC-based VPN"
#                                     references)
#   tun-rs                "=2.8.2"   (TUN interface — pinned to an
#                                     audited version because the
#                                     CGO-less tun-interface
#                                     primitive is the privileged
#                                     attack surface of the entire
#                                     binary; pinning prevents
#                                     supply-chain attacks via
#                                     mid-life-cycle dep updates)
#   tokio                            (async runtime)
#   socket2 + libc + ipnet           (low-level socket + IP-address
#                                     manipulation for the routing-
#                                     table push-rules)
#   figment + serde + serde_json     (TOML + env-var config loader
#                                     supporting layered overrides:
#                                     env var > config file > default)
#   clap (with derive)               (CLI parser — the minimal
#                                     surface above)
#
# Quincy is "WireGuard but over QUIC with post-quantum cryptography."
# WireGuard's wire protocol predates standardized post-quantum KEM
# selection (Kyber wasn't standardized until 2024) and uses a
# non-extensible Noise-IKpsk2-derived handshake that has no clean
# upgrade path to PQ.  Quincy's premise: build a tunnel over QUIC
# (which already standardized post-quantum hybrid KEM via aws-lc-rs's
# Kyber768-X25519 in 2024), keep the WireGuard-style TUN-interface
# UX, and ship today.  Operator workflow: write a server.toml
# specifying the QUIC listen endpoint + TUN device name + assignable
# client IP range + TLS cert/key + the user-database, write a
# client.toml on each client with the corresponding QUIC server
# endpoint + auth credentials, and `quincy-server` / `quincy-client`
# bring the tunnel up.  The `--env-prefix` flag lets all config keys
# be overridden by env vars for container deployments where the
# config-file approach is awkward.
#
